snippet.textDisplay: When the 49ers were negotiating with Jimmy, I argued that he was worth at least 30 million.  I believe he was signed to 27.5 per so I thought the 49ers got about an eight percent discount.  But if Jimmy were a free agent right now he could probably demand 35 per.  But he probably has at least the third-quickest release in the league — maybe only Rodgers and Rivers are quicker — and Jimmy is more accurate than advertised — his completion percentage is near 70 percent.  His TD-2-INT ratio needs to improve — he’s 2:1 and should be 3:1 — but this should only improve as he gets more and more used to his receivers.  And of course his winning percentage as a starter is over 80.  ‘Nuff said.

snippet.textDisplay: Patriots are THE Premiere SYSTEM Offense Team.     As such, a scrambling QB isn't part of the Patriot design.     The Patriot SYSTEM requires 2 elements:    1)  WR attaining separation   2)  WR running a precise route, as per the DESIGNED PLAY CALL.    Brady will always tell you:  "I need to know how each play will end, BEFORE the play is put in motion."    Other QBs like  Mahomes, D. Watson, A. Rogers, etc.,  play an  'Ad Hoc' style.      Tell me, Colin, which style of Offence has won more NFL games, more Division Titles-in-a-row, and more Super Bowls in the last 2 decades???   That's right, Colin.... the Patriot System.      NOT the Ad Hoc scrambling style.       I think you have misdiagnosed this segment, my good friend.    Blessings,    John.

snippet.textDisplay: I believe that all the blame that Brady is getting for this year is not justified. The team has to support different aspects of the offense, the offensive line aids the running game and the throwing through actively creating gaps and protecting the quarterback. Better protection means more time to throw and more time to get open. We also have to consider the level of detail that is required to play WR in this offense, some times you have to block, some beat double coverage, etc...but always being in the right spot st the right time. Except Jules, the rest of the receivers have been out of place in a lot of situations and the frustration was palpable. He is still the same person, but the offense let him down this year.

snippet.textDisplay: This is absurd. This is such a lazy analysis. Any decent QB needs blockers to give him the extended second or two. They might scramble here and there but they need protection to find receivers. N’Keal Harry needs time to get better and on the same page with the offence program and Tom. I invite Colin to go and watch the one game Brady played with Antonio Brown. The WR that has never played with Brady was pretty in sync with him and now wants to only play with Tom Brady. Watch all the playoff games Brady has played in his career and see the amount of big plays to the side-lines and game winning drives to WR. This theory that his system is rigid is absurd and lazy. This is not his system. It is a team system and he has input in it and he should because it will be mainly based on his attributes. No offensive coordinator puts together an entire system with the head coach based on extended plays and QB's ability to scramble for 5 seconds. There might be a play or two here and there but that is it. Brady's ability to throw to WR is not even debatable and Brady has never been the king of scramblers, not even in his twenties. He had better protection and supporting cast. Football is a team sport.

snippet.textDisplay: It is easy to pick the Vikings, but, why?  Because you might be suffering from the illusion of recentness.  We often think that last week affects this week.  It is less true than we think.  We assume that the Vikings "found something" last week.  We think that D. Cook now makes the difference.  But all of that was last week.  Here's the difference-- The Saints tend to find a way to lose big games at home.  But the 49ers find a way to win those same games.  Folks think that the Vikings match up well.  But the 49ers have found ways to re-invent themselves each week in order to compensate for bad match-ups.  I do think this is going to be a close game and, sure, the Vikings are capable of beating the 49ers.  But the 49ers are battle tested and have played multiple games that have literally gone the entire 60 minutes.  They will not quit.  For the Vikings to win, they will have to play their best football for 60+ minutes of game clock without any let down.  They did it last week.  But can they do it consistently?  The Vikings are not exactly the picture of consistency this season.  So, no I don't think so.

snippet.textDisplay:
Cowherd shoulda been a lawyer. He can take a lousy argument and make it sound good.
1. Randy Moss... that was arguably the best offensive season in NFL history.
2. It IS Belichick's 'fault'. Belichick clearly assigns a max value to every position so that he can distribute the money most efficiently.
Belichick clearly believes that wide receivers are overpaid based on their ACTUAL impact on winning.
a. QB's are far and away most valuable in the current game.... it's worthwhile spending the $$'s/ draft pick on a good prospect.
b. The one anomaly is running backs. A good one is very valuable, but longevity of RB's is wildly unpredictable.... no point in gambling by paying a lot of $$'s for a RB.
3. A well-choreographed short game is hard to develop, but deadly if you can work out the timing between QB and receivers.
Remember: extended plays happen through good protection, too.
